## IMPROVEMENT 1 — ZDOG LAYER TYPE

### Why Zdog for explainer videos

Zdog renders 3D geometry using 2D canvas/SVG drawing.
The result looks like flat vector illustration with 3D depth.
This is PERFECT for whiteboard explainer content:
  - Rotating molecular models
  - 3D bar charts and graphs
  - Spinning globes and maps
  - Product diagrams with depth
  - Step-by-step assembly animations
  - Network topology diagrams

The aesthetic matches Canvas2D's hand-drawn feel much better
than full WebGL Three.js scenes. Zdog scenes feel designed,
not rendered.

### License
MIT — fully commercial safe.

### CDN
https://unpkg.com/zdog@1/dist/zdog.dist.min.js

### Layer type addition

```ts
interface ZdogLayer extends BaseLayer {
  type: 'zdog'
  zoom: number              // scene zoom, default 4
  dragRotate: boolean       // interactive rotation (preview only)
  autoSpin: boolean         // continuous rotation
  spinSpeed: number         // rotation per frame, default 0.01
  bgColor: string | null    // null = transparent
}
```

### Zdog scene HTML template

```html
<div id="{layer.id}" class="inkframe-layer" style="
  opacity: {layer.opacity};
  z-index: {layer.zIndex};">
  
  <canvas id="{layer.id}-canvas"
    width="1920" height="1080"
    style="display:block;">
  </canvas>
</div>

<script src="https://unpkg.com/zdog@1/dist/zdog.dist.min.js"></script>
<script>
  setTimeout(() => {
    const canvas = document.getElementById('{layer.id}-canvas');
    
    {layer.generatedCode}
    // Generated code creates illo, shapes, and the animate loop
    
  }, {layer.startAt * 1000});
</script>
```

### Zdog generation prompt

```
You are generating a Zdog pseudo-3D illustration for Inkframe.
Zdog renders flat vector-style 3D using canvas 2D drawing.
The visual style is clean, designed, illustrative — like a vector
diagram with depth. Perfect for diagrams, charts, and models.

ZDOG API (complete reference — stay within this):

  // Create the illustration
  const illo = new Zdog.Illustration({
    element: canvas,           // the canvas element
    zoom: {zoom},              // scale factor
    dragRotate: false,         // never true in export
    resize: false,
    width: 1920,
    height: 1080,
  });

  // SHAPES — add to illo or to other shapes
  new Zdog.Ellipse({ addTo, diameter, stroke, color, fill, translate, rotate })
  new Zdog.Rect({ addTo, width, height, stroke, color, fill, translate, rotate })
  new Zdog.RoundedRect({ addTo, width, height, cornerRadius, stroke, color })
  new Zdog.Polygon({ addTo, radius, sides, stroke, color, fill })
  new Zdog.Shape({ addTo, path: [{x,y,z},...], stroke, color, closed, fill })
  new Zdog.Cylinder({ addTo, diameter, length, stroke, color, fill, backface })
  new Zdog.Cone({ addTo, diameter, length, stroke, color })
  new Zdog.Box({ addTo, width, height, depth, stroke, color, fill,
                 leftFace, rightFace, topFace, bottomFace, frontFace, rearFace })
  new Zdog.Hemisphere({ addTo, diameter, stroke, color, fill, backface })
  
  // GROUPS — for organizing and animating together
  const group = new Zdog.Anchor({ addTo: illo, translate, rotate, scale });
  // Add shapes to group with addTo: group
  
  // TEXT — use Zfont for text on shapes
  // Note: Zfont requires loading a font. Skip text — use HTML overlay instead.
  
  // TRANSLATION: { x, y, z }  where x=right, y=down, z=toward camera
  // ROTATION:    { x, y, z }  in radians
  // COLORS:      hex strings from PALETTE

  // ANIMATION LOOP
  let startTime = null;
  function animate(timestamp) {
    if (!startTime) startTime = timestamp;
    const elapsed = (timestamp - startTime) / 1000; // seconds
    
    // Rotate, translate, or modify shapes based on elapsed time
    group.rotate.y = elapsed * {spinSpeed};
    
    illo.updateRenderGraph();
    
    if (elapsed < {duration}) {
      requestAnimationFrame(animate);
    }
  }
  requestAnimationFrame(animate);

PALETTE: {palette}  — use these colors for all shapes
DURATION: {duration}s
CANVAS CENTER: x=0, y=0 in Zdog space (Zdog is centered by default)
ZOOM: {zoom}  — at zoom=4, a shape with diameter=40 appears ~160px

OUTPUT FORMAT:
{
  "sceneCode": "// complete Zdog scene code as a string"
}

RULES:
- Use Box, Cylinder, Ellipse, and Polygon as primary shapes
- Use Anchor groups to organize related shapes
- Animate via rotate.y += speed in the RAF loop for spinning effects
- Stagger appearance: translate shapes outside canvas at start,
  animate them in using lerp: shape.translate.y += (target - current) * 0.05
- Use backface: false on shapes facing away from camera
- All colors from PALETTE only
- Maximum ~20 shapes for performance
- Canvas text: use a separate HTML overlay layer instead of Zfont
- dragRotate: ALWAYS false (WVC doesn't have mouse events)

WHAT TO BUILD:
Based on the user prompt, choose the right Zdog shapes:
  Molecule/atom model → Sphere (Hemisphere×2) + Cylinder bonds + Anchor groups
  3D bar chart → Box shapes of varying heights + Anchor base
  Globe → Hemisphere layers stacked + Ellipse rings
  Gear/mechanical → Polygon teeth + Cylinder body
  Network diagram → Ellipse nodes + Shape connector lines
  Product box → Box with different face colors
  DNA helix → Two Shape paths wound around a Cylinder
  Hierarchy/org chart → Box nodes + Shape connectors in 3D space

Previous scene context: {previousSummary}
```

### Zdog tool filter integration

Add to the tool filter chips in Agent Control Panel:
[✓ Zdog (flat 3D)]

Add to rules/3d.md:
```
CHOOSING BETWEEN THREE.JS AND ZDOG:

Use Zdog when:
- The scene needs a clean, illustrative, vector-design aesthetic
- Subject is a diagram, model, or chart (not a landscape or environment)
- You want the 3D to feel designed, not rendered
- Example prompts: molecule, gear, org chart, 3D bar chart, globe, product box

Use Three.js when:
- The scene needs realistic materials, lighting, or shadows
- Subject is environmental (space, room, landscape)
- You need particle systems, shaders, or complex geometry
- Example prompts: space scene, particle explosion, shader effect, terrain
```

