## IMPROVEMENT 2 — 3D COMPONENT LIBRARY

### The core problem

Claude generating arbitrary Three.js produces poor results
because it invents geometry, lighting, and camera from scratch.
The fix: pre-built, tested, high-quality Three.js components
Claude assembles instead of invents.

Think of it like the 2D asset library but for 3D scene pieces.

### Component structure

```ts
interface ThreeDComponent {
  id: string
  name: string
  category: ThreeDCategory
  tags: string[]
  description: string   // for Claude: when to use this component
  
  // Self-contained JS function string
  // Receives: scene, palette, seed
  // Returns: { group, update(t) }
  // t = elapsed seconds
  buildFn: string
  
  // Preview info
  thumbnail: string     // base64 PNG
  animates: boolean     // does it animate?
  interactive: boolean  // responds to camera/mouse?
}

type ThreeDCategory =
  | 'objects'         // primary 3D objects
  | 'environments'    // backgrounds, skyboxes, floors
  | 'lighting-rigs'   // pre-configured lighting setups
  | 'cameras'         // camera preset configurations
  | 'particles'       // particle systems
  | 'text'            // 3D text setups
  | 'effects'         // post-processing, shaders
  | 'data-viz'        // 3D charts, graphs
```

### Core component library (build these first)

**Lighting rigs (most important — bad lighting kills 3D quality):**

```ts
{
  id: 'lighting-studio',
  name: 'Studio Lighting',
  description: 'Soft professional studio setup with key, fill, and rim lights. Use for product shots and object showcases.',
  buildFn: `
    function build(scene, palette) {
      // Ambient — very soft overall light
      const ambient = new THREE.AmbientLight(0xffffff, 0.3);
      scene.add(ambient);
      
      // Key light — main directional from upper left
      const key = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xffffff, 1.2);
      key.position.set(-5, 8, 5);
      key.castShadow = true;
      key.shadow.mapSize.width = 2048;
      key.shadow.mapSize.height = 2048;
      scene.add(key);
      
      // Fill light — softer from right, warm tint
      const fill = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xfff4e0, 0.4);
      fill.position.set(5, 2, 3);
      scene.add(fill);
      
      // Rim light — behind object, cool blue edge
      const rim = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xd0e8ff, 0.6);
      rim.position.set(0, 3, -8);
      scene.add(rim);
      
      return { update: (t) => {} };
    }
  `
},
{
  id: 'lighting-dramatic',
  name: 'Dramatic Lighting',
  description: 'High contrast single key light with dark shadows. Use for dramatic reveals, important objects.',
  buildFn: `...`
},
{
  id: 'lighting-soft-overhead',
  name: 'Soft Overhead',
  description: 'Even overhead lighting, minimal shadows. Use for diagrams and technical content where clarity matters more than drama.',
  buildFn: `...`
},
{
  id: 'lighting-neon',
  name: 'Neon Environment',
  description: 'Dark background with colored point lights from palette colors. Use for tech, data, or futuristic scenes.',
  buildFn: `
    function build(scene, palette) {
      scene.background = new THREE.Color(0x050510);
      
      // Point lights in palette colors
      palette.forEach((color, i) => {
        const light = new THREE.PointLight(color, 2, 20);
        light.position.set(
          Math.cos(i * Math.PI / 2) * 8,
          Math.sin(i * 0.7) * 4,
          Math.sin(i * Math.PI / 2) * 8
        );
        scene.add(light);
      });
      
      const ambient = new THREE.AmbientLight(0x111122, 0.5);
      scene.add(ambient);
      
      return { update: (t) => {
        // Slowly pulse lights
        scene.children
          .filter(c => c.isPointLight)
          .forEach((light, i) => {
            light.intensity = 1.5 + Math.sin(t * 0.5 + i) * 0.5;
          });
      }};
    }
  `
}
```

**Camera presets:**

```ts
{
  id: 'camera-orbit-slow',
  name: 'Slow Orbit',
  description: 'Camera slowly orbits around center. Classic for product reveals and object showcases.',
  buildFn: `
    function build(camera, duration) {
      const radius = camera.position.length();
      const startAngle = Math.atan2(camera.position.z, camera.position.x);
      
      return { update: (t) => {
        const angle = startAngle + (t / duration) * Math.PI * 2 * 0.3;
        camera.position.x = Math.cos(angle) * radius;
        camera.position.z = Math.sin(angle) * radius;
        camera.lookAt(0, 0, 0);
      }};
    }
  `
},
{
  id: 'camera-pullback',
  name: 'Dramatic Pullback',
