## IMPROVEMENT 3 — THREE.JS GENERATION QUALITY

When the agent does generate Three.js from scratch
(not using components), enforce these quality standards.

### Update rules/three.md

```markdown
# Three.js Scene Generation Rules

## ALWAYS start with quality renderer settings

const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ antialias: true, alpha: true });
renderer.shadowMap.enabled = true;
renderer.shadowMap.type = THREE.PCFSoftShadowMap;
renderer.toneMapping = THREE.ACESFilmicToneMapping;
renderer.toneMappingExposure = 1.2;
renderer.outputColorSpace = THREE.SRGBColorSpace;

## ALWAYS use physically-based materials

// WRONG — flat, plastic-looking:
new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ color: 0xff0000 })

// RIGHT — physically realistic:
new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({
  color: palette[0],
  roughness: 0.4,      // 0 = mirror, 1 = totally rough
  metalness: 0.1,      // 0 = plastic, 1 = metal
})

// For glass/transparent:
new THREE.MeshPhysicalMaterial({
  color: palette[0],
  transparent: true,
  opacity: 0.3,
  roughness: 0,
  metalness: 0,
  transmission: 0.9,
})

## ALWAYS set up 3-point lighting minimum

Never use just AmbientLight alone — scenes look flat and washed out.
Always: ambient (low) + directional key + directional fill minimum.
See lighting-studio component for reference.

## Camera positioning guide

Too close = distorted, claustrophobic
Too far = tiny objects, lost detail

For a scene with objects of radius ~1-2 units:
  camera.position.set(0, 4, 10) — good default
  camera.position.set(0, 8, 0)  — top down
  camera.position.set(7, 5, 7)  — isometric feel

ALWAYS call camera.lookAt(0, 0, 0) after positioning.

## Smooth animation easing

// WRONG — linear, mechanical:
object.rotation.y += 0.01

// RIGHT — eased with sine:
object.rotation.y = Math.sin(t * 0.5) * Math.PI * 0.25

// RIGHT — smooth interpolation to target:
object.position.y += (targetY - object.position.y) * 0.05

## Shadows

For shadows to work:
1. renderer.shadowMap.enabled = true
2. light.castShadow = true
3. mesh.castShadow = true (the object)
4. floor.receiveShadow = true (the surface)

Without step 4, objects float unrealistically.

## Scale guide

One Three.js unit ≈ one "unit" in scene space.
Keep objects between 0.5 and 3 units radius.
Camera at 8-15 units distance.
Floor at y = -2 to -4.

## What NOT to generate

Never use:
- THREE.CapsuleGeometry (not in r128)
- OrbitControls (not on CDN)
- ES module imports (THREE is a global)
- GLTFLoader (no .glb files available)
- EnvironmentMap/HDR (no HDR files available)
- TextGeometry alone (requires FontLoader, complex)

## Colors

Always use PALETTE array, never hardcoded hex values.
new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: new THREE.Color(PALETTE[0]) })
THREE.Color accepts hex strings directly.

## Performance

Keep polygon count reasonable for headless Chrome:
  Simple scenes: < 50k triangles total
  Medium scenes: < 150k triangles
  Complex scenes: < 300k triangles

SphereGeometry(1, 32, 32) = ~2k triangles — fine
SphereGeometry(1, 128, 128) = ~32k triangles — too many for one sphere

## Determinism for WVC export

NEVER use Math.random() — use seeded mulberry32.
NEVER use Date.now() — use the t parameter from RAF.
Same seed + same elapsed time = same frame = deterministic export.
```

### Material quality presets

Inject these as constants in every Three.js scene HTML:

```js
// Pre-configured material recipes
const MATERIALS = {
  plastic: (color) => new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({
    color: new THREE.Color(color),
    roughness: 0.6, metalness: 0.0
  }),
  metal: (color) => new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({
    color: new THREE.Color(color),
    roughness: 0.2, metalness: 0.9
  }),
  glass: (color) => new THREE.MeshPhysicalMaterial({
    color: new THREE.Color(color),
    transparent: true, opacity: 0.25,
    roughness: 0.0, metalness: 0.0,
    transmission: 0.9,
  }),
  matte: (color) => new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({
    color: new THREE.Color(color),
    roughness: 1.0, metalness: 0.0
  }),
  glow: (color) => new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({
    color: new THREE.Color(color),
    emissive: new THREE.Color(color),
    emissiveIntensity: 0.4,
    roughness: 0.3, metalness: 0.1,
  }),
};

// Agent uses: MATERIALS.metal(PALETTE[0])
// instead of manually specifying roughness/metalness
```

### Agent 3D selection guide update

Inject into Scene Maker agent:

```
3D LAYER SELECTION GUIDE:

Step 1: Does the scene need illustrative/diagram 3D?
  → Use Zdog layer
  → Molecule, gear, chart, globe, network diagram, product box

Step 2: Does the scene need real 3D with quality rendering?
  → Use Three.js layer via assemble_three_scene
  → Choose components: lighting + camera + 1-3 objects + environment
  → Use assemble_three_scene, NOT generate_three_layer

Step 3: Does the scene need something no component covers?
  → Use generate_three_layer with the Three.js rules
  → ALWAYS start from quality renderer + 3-point lighting
  → ALWAYS use MATERIALS.* presets
  → ALWAYS use seeded randomness

NEVER generate Three.js from scratch when a component exists for it.
Check available components first every time.
```

